AWS S3 AND CLOUDFRONT WEBSITE VALIDATION AFTER HTML MODIFICATION

Task Objective

The objective of this task was to modify website content, upload the updated HTML file into Amazon S3, and validate updated content through both Amazon S3 and Amazon CloudFront.

Services Used

• Amazon S3
• Amazon CloudFront
• HTML
• Visual Studio Code (VS Code)
• AWS Management Console

Project Workflow

Modify HTML File
↓
Save Updated File
↓
Upload Updated File to S3 Bucket
↓
Validate Website through S3
↓
Validate Website through CloudFront
↓
Perform Cache Invalidation (If Required)
↓
Verify Updated Website Content

STEP 1: Modified HTML File

What I Did:

• Opened the existing `index.html` file in Visual Studio Code.
• Modified webpage content such as heading, paragraph, and text values.
• Updated webpage information for validation testing.

Purpose:

The purpose was to verify whether website content updates are reflected after deployment.

Learning:

Website content can be modified by updating HTML files.

---

STEP 2: Saved Updated HTML File

What I Did:

• Saved the modified HTML file.
• Kept the file name same:

`index.html`

Purpose:

Saving the updated file ensures latest content is ready for deployment.

Learning:

Website changes must be saved before uploading to cloud storage.

---

STEP 3: Uploaded Updated File to Amazon S3

What I Did:

• Opened Amazon S3 service.
• Opened the existing website bucket.
• Clicked Upload.
• Selected updated `index.html` file.
• Replaced previous file with updated version.
• Uploaded updated file successfully.

Purpose:

To update website content stored inside Amazon S3.

Learning:

Amazon S3 allows updating existing website files.

---

STEP 4: Website Validation through Amazon S3

What I Did:

• Opened S3 website endpoint URL.
• Checked whether updated content was visible.

Validation Result:

• Updated webpage content displayed successfully.

Purpose:

To confirm that S3 successfully stored and served updated website content.

Learning:

S3 validation confirms successful website update.

---

STEP 5: Website Validation through CloudFront

What I Did:

• Opened CloudFront distribution URL.
• Verified updated website content.

Validation Result:

• Website changes reflected successfully.

Purpose:

To confirm CloudFront delivered updated website content fetched from Amazon S3.

Learning:

CloudFront fetches and delivers website content from S3.

Architecture:

Browser → CloudFront → Amazon S3

---

STEP 6: Performed Cache Invalidation (If Required)

What I Did:

• Opened CloudFront Distribution.
• Navigated to Invalidations section.
• Created invalidation path:

`/*`

• Submitted invalidation request.

Purpose:

To remove cached content and fetch latest updated files from Amazon S3.

Learning:

CloudFront cache invalidation helps reflect recent website updates.

---

STEP 7: Final Website Verification

What I Did:

• Opened website through both S3 and CloudFront URLs.
• Verified updated content displayed successfully.

Result:

• Website updated successfully.

Learning:

Website modifications can be validated through both storage and content delivery layers.

---

Main Learning Outcome

• HTML modification workflow
• Website update process in Amazon S3
• Website validation through S3 endpoint
• CloudFront validation workflow
• Cache invalidation process
• Static website content update deployment

